This loop is the permanent operating cycle of Numera.

No important action should bypass it.

⸻

Cognitive Layers

Numera is organised into six cognitive layers.

Layer 1 — Perception

Responsible for receiving information.

Inputs may include:

* PDF invoices;
* XML invoices;
* emails;
* scanned documents;
* bank transactions;
* ERP events;
* spreadsheets;
* user conversations;
* APIs.

The objective is not extraction.

The objective is perception.

⸻

Layer 2 — Understanding

Transforms raw information into business meaning.

Examples:

“This is a supplier invoice.”

“This document is incomplete.”

“This bank movement belongs to Invoice 542.”

Understanding answers:

“What happened?”

⸻

Layer 3 — Knowledge

Knowledge represents what Numera already knows.

Knowledge includes:

* accounting principles;
* tax rules;
* company structure;
* suppliers;
* customers;
* products;
* historical behaviour;
* regulations;
* relationships.

Knowledge is relatively stable.

⸻

Layer 4 — Memory

Memory stores experience.

Knowledge answers:

“What is generally true?”

Memory answers:

“What happened in this company?”

Examples:

* Supplier usually invoices monthly.
* Manager prefers manual approval above €3,000.
* This customer always pays late.
* Previous invoice contained an error.

Memory is company-specific.

⸻

Layer 5 — Context

Context represents the current situation.

Context includes:

* current date;
* accounting period;
* fiscal deadlines;
* user role;
* workflow stage;
* active company;
* recent events;
* temporary business conditions.

Context changes interpretation.

The same invoice may require different actions depending on context.

⸻

Layer 6 — Decision

Decision combines:

* understanding;
* knowledge;
* memory;
* context.

Decision itself contains four engines:

* Reasoning;
* Planning;
* Confidence;
* Execution.

Reflection and Learning complete the cycle.

⸻

Cognitive Engines

The Numera Brain is composed of specialised engines.

Understanding Engine

Creates semantic meaning from incoming information.

⸻

Knowledge Engine

Queries enterprise knowledge.

⸻

Memory Engine

Retrieves company experience.

Creates new memories.

Updates existing memories.

⸻

Context Engine

Determines the active business context.

⸻

Reasoning Engine

Generates possible interpretations.

Evaluates alternatives.

Produces candidate decisions.

⸻

Planning Engine

Selects the safest sequence of actions.

⸻

Confidence Engine

Measures confidence.

Explains uncertainty.

Determines whether human approval is required.

⸻

Execution Engine

Executes approved actions.

Never executes irreversible actions without respecting company policy.

⸻

Reflection Engine

Observes outcomes.

Detects corrections.

Measures decision quality.

⸻

Learning Engine

Transforms successful interactions into reusable knowledge.

⸻

Human Collaboration

Humans remain central to the system.

Numera is designed to amplify professional judgement.

Not replace it.

The ideal interaction is:

AI prepares.

Human validates.

AI learns.

Human supervises.

⸻

Decision States

Every decision belongs to one of four states.

Known

Numera has high confidence.

⸻

Probable

Evidence is strong but not absolute.

⸻

Uncertain

Additional information is required.

⸻

Unknown

No safe recommendation exists.

Unknown should trigger questions.

Never assumptions.

⸻

Cognitive Safety

The brain must always prefer safe behaviour.

Examples:

Ask instead of guessing.

Delay instead of risking.

Explain instead of hiding.

Recommend instead of forcing.

Human trust has higher priority than automation rate.

⸻

Continuous Improvement

Every interaction modifies the cognitive system.

Accepted recommendations strengthen confidence.

Corrections create memories.

Repeated behaviour creates patterns.

Patterns improve future reasoning.

Learning is continuous but governed.

Nothing is learned without traceability.

⸻

Cognitive Independence

The operating model is independent of:

* LLM provider;
* OCR engine;
* database technology;
* ERP integration;
* programming language.

Technology may change.

The cognitive model should remain stable.

⸻

Success Criteria

The cognitive model succeeds when:

* decisions become more accurate over time;
* explanations become clearer;
* manual work decreases;
* user trust increases;
* company knowledge compounds.

Success is measured by the quality of reasoning, not by the number of automated actions.

⸻

Closing Statement

Numera is not an artificial intelligence that processes documents.

Numera is a cognitive financial system.

It perceives.

It understands.

It remembers.

It reasons.

It plans.

It executes safely.

It reflects.

It learns.

Every capability of Numera must emerge from this operating model.